  "prompt": "What is the procedure of getting admission into IIT for NRIs?",
  "response": "Getting admission into an Indian Institute of Technology (IIT) for Non-Resident Indians (NRIs) involves several steps, which are generally similar to those for Indian residents, with some variations. Here\u2019s a detailed procedure:\n\n1. **Eligibility Criteria**:\n   - NRIs must meet the same educational qualifications as Indian students. This typically means completing high school (12th grade or equivalent) with subjects such as Physics, Chemistry, and Mathematics.\n   - They must also meet age criteria, which usually is that the candidate should be born on or after October 1, 1998 (for JEE Main conducted in 2023).\n\n2. **Entrance Exams**:\n   - **JEE Main**: NRIs must appear for the Joint Entrance Examination (JEE) Main, which is the preliminary examination. This exam is conducted by the National Testing Agency (NTA) and is usually held twice a year.\n   - **JEE Advanced**: If the candidate qualifies in JEE Main and is among the top candidates, they can then appear for JEE Advanced. NRIs need to score within the top ranks to be eligible for IITs.\n   - **SAT Subject Tests**: Some IITs may also consider SAT Subject Tests in Mathematics Level 2, Physics, and Chemistry for NRIs. However, this is not the common route and varies by IIT.\n\n3. **Application Process**:\n   - Register for JEE Main through the official NTA website.\n   - After qualifying JEE Main, register for JEE Advanced.\n   - Follow the specific guidelines for NRIs provided on the official JEE Advanced website, which may include providing proof of NRI status and other documentation.\n   - Some IITs have seats reserved for foreign nationals under the Direct Admission of Students Abroad (DASA) scheme, which may have different requirements and application processes.\n\n4. **Counseling and Seat Allocation**:\n   - After the results of JEE Advanced are announced, candidates need to participate in the Joint Seat Allocation Authority (JoSAA) counseling process.\n   - During counseling, candidates will fill in their preferences for IITs and courses.\n   - Seat allocation is based on the rank obtained in JEE Advanced and the preferences filled during counseling.\n\n5. **Documentation**:\n   - Valid passport and proof of NRI status.\n   - Transcripts and certificates from previous educational institutions, including the equivalence certificate if the qualification is from a foreign board.\n   - Scorecards from JEE Main and JEE Advanced (or SAT Subject Tests if applicable).\n   - Other documents as specified by the specific IIT and the JoSAA.\n\n6. **Visa and Other Formalities**:\n   - NRIs admitted to IITs will need to ensure they have a valid student visa to study in India.\n   - They may also need to complete other formalities such as health insurance, accommodation arrangements, and travel preparations.\n\nIt\u2019s important to check the specific requirements of the IIT and the DASA scheme, if applicable, as they may have additional or slightly different procedures for NRIs. Always refer to the latest official guidelines on the IIT and JEE websites for the most accurate and updated information.",
